Al Golin had a vision for McDonald’s early on that shaped who we are today, and made us proud to tell our story. He elevated that story beyond food to make sure McDonald’s had a place in communities by helping create Ronald McDonald House Charities and the McDonald’s All-American Games. It is with heavy hearts that we say goodbye to our long-time friend, who passed away over the weekend at age 87. We want to say thank you to Al and his family for his years of dedication to our brand, and being an overall kind and positive man who was integral to who we are.
 
Rest in peace, Al.

Today we’ve announced that by mid-2018, all Quarter Pounder burgers at the majority of our restaurants will be cooked with fresh beef.
 
It’s the latest in a series of bold, tangible changes we’ve made for our customers over the last two years. We’ve accelerated the pace of changes to our menu, and fresh beef burgers, cooked right when ordered, are the latest step we’re taking to raise the bar.
 
And we’re just getting started. We can’t wait to show you what’s next.

Congratulations to Loraine Maurer who celebrated 44 years of working at McDonald’s in Evansville, IN last Thursday! 
 
With her infectious smile and love of McDonald’s, the 94-year-old has won the hearts of coworkers and customers alike. 
 
In fact, she prefers to call them friends, not customers—because they keep her going and they do things outside of work together. 
 
We want to say thank you to her for making such a big impact on McDonald’s and the friends that she continues to serve!

We want to extend a heartfelt thank you to a very special McDonald’s crew member, TQ, who went above and beyond to make sure a customer had an experience to remember. After Bonnie Kandel’s 7-year old son Leif, who has autism, saw a classmate with a McDonald's Teen Titans Happy Meal toy at school he knew he wanted one for himself. When he and his mom walked into the Speedway, IN restaurant last week, they learned that the current Happy Meals toy was Lego Batman instead of the Teen Titans toy that Leif wanted so badly. Bonnie explained to TQ how much the toy meant to Leif and TQ quickly took action, working with her manager and taking time out of her day to find the toys for Leif. According to his mom, Leif’s excitement was notable, he sleeps with them and takes them with him whenever they leave the house. 
 
Through her actions, TQ demonstrated to all of us that even the smallest things can make a big difference in the lives of other people. She showed us that she’s not only a great crewmember who takes care of every customer, but also a great person who understands how inspiring kindness can be. TQ is an inspiration and McDonald’s is proud to be a part of an amazing story!

We’d also like to send a shout out to Love What Matters for sharing great stories like this that shine a light on the positive things that people do for each other. http://huff.to/2knrlLs

Nothing is more important to us than the safety of our customers, including the toys and children’s products we offer them. McDonald’s has decided to voluntarily recall the Step-iT Activity Wristbands in the U.S. and Canada after recently receiving reports of skin irritation and burns upon wearing the wristband. No other toys or products are involved in this voluntary recall, and the recall has no impact on other Happy Meal products in markets outside the U.S., Canada and the Caribbean.
link_name: McDonald's USA and Canada Voluntarily Recall STEP-iT Activity Bands

Happy 103rd George Day! 

Over the past 30 years, George Yamamoto has bought countless Apple Pies and McCafé coffee for friends and neighbors in Monterey Park, California. The community came together to treat him for his 103rd birthday. City council members, staff and even Ronald McDonald came out to celebrate George’s decades of loyalty and friendship.
